{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\n\nAdd a CI job that runs an end-to-end rebar CLI golden path\n(install → init → create → ready → claim → close) in a throwaway git repo, so the\nquickstart's commands can never silently rot again. This is the core\nmaintenance-burden reducer for the P0 defects.\n\nReuse, do not re-author: `scripts/probe-rebar.sh` already exercises the full CLI\nsurface end-to-end against the real engine in an isolated temp `REBAR_ROOT`. This\nticket wires it (or a trimmed init→create→ready→claim→close subset that mirrors the\nREADME quickstart) into CI as a gating job.\n\n- Add the job to `.github/workflows/test.yml` (CI's source of truth), invoking the\n  existing probe script.\n- Ensure it runs on a clean install of the package so it also catches\n  packaging/entry-point regressions.\n- Keep it fast and hermetic (temp dir, no network, no shared state).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A CI job runs the golden-path probe and FAILS the build if any of\n      init/create/ready/claim/close changes exit code or expected output.\n- [ ] The job runs against an installed rebar (not just `src` on `PYTHONPATH`).\n- [ ] A deliberately broken quickstart command is demonstrably caught by the job\n      (note the manual verification in a comment).\n- [ ] The job executes the **actual commands extracted from the README quickstart fenced block** (parse the fenced block, run those exact lines in a throwaway repo), so a wrong command *printed* in the README — e.g. `session-log` missing its `append` verb — fails CI. Executability of an independent probe is NOT sufficient; the README *text* itself must be what runs (closes epic finding G6).\n\nFiles: `.github/workflows/test.yml`, `scripts/probe-rebar.sh`."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783815900233724001,"uuid":"96063159-c901-46a4-8ef4-a96e300b5273"}